1) “Gratitude is luck” (make it operational)

It’s not literally luck, but it acts like it.

Gratitude trains your attention to notice and reuse what’s already working.

Mechanism:
	•	attention shifts → you spot opportunities you would’ve missed
	•	interpretation shifts → you treat events as usable, not hostile
	•	behavior shifts → you follow through more consistently

So the downstream effect looks like luck.

Working version:

Gratitude = attention reweighting → better decisions → compounding outcomes

Use it as a practice, not a claim:
	•	daily: “what worked + why did it work + how do I reuse it”

⸻

2) “Feeling watched” (what’s actually going on)

There isn’t a reliable built-in sense that detects unseen watchers. What you’re noticing is a threat/attention system that overgeneralizes.

Pieces involved:
	•	Amygdala / salience network → flags potential threat
	•	Superior temporal sulcus → tracks gaze/intent of others
	•	Predictive processing → brain guesses “could someone be watching?” when cues are ambiguous

In low info environments, the system errs on the side of:

“assume observation → stay safe”

That’s adaptive, but it can also misfire.

Useful takeaway:

Treat “I feel watched” as a signal of heightened vigilance, not evidence.

⸻

3) Self-sabotage (your insight, cleaned up)

You nailed it:

fear of getting what you want + fear of losing it

So the system avoids both by… stalling itself.

Pattern:
	•	desire → anxiety → delay / overcomplicate / distract → relief → repeat

Fix (simple, not easy):

Act at a level you can afford to lose.

	•	shrink the move
	•	make it reversible
	•	execute anyway

You’re not trying to eliminate fear—you’re routing around it.

